Hello from nature preschool!

We are searching for the following items to upcycle for our outdoor classroom!

PVC pipe pieces and connectors
Pots, pans, cookie sheets, wooden spoons, tongs
Clothespins and clothesline
Milk crates
An old retired canoe or a rowboat
A slide- from a swing set or any free standing slide (we want to build it into a hill)
Sheet of plexiglass
Spray bottles
Empty clear jars- for bug catching

If you would like to donate any of the above items, they may be dropped off to the ECC office.

Thank you,
Amiee and Erika

post_text:
Welcome back to Environmental Science 2020-2021
All classes grade K-8 will have Environmental Science once a week and Ms. Holly and Mr. Shawn are excited to teach your students outside on our 62 acre campus. It is important that students are prepared for all weather, as we are going to be outside as much as possible.
-Ponchos/rain coats and mud boots for rainy days (we won't be going out with thunder or lightening)
-Close toed shoes
-Reusable water bottles
-Hats/sunscreen (apply at home) for sunny days
-If it's been rainy I would also suggest spraying your child with bug spray on their science day

Environmental Science Schedule
Mondays: Wilcome-K, Potter-K, Brown-K, Lamoreaux-Y5, McMann-4
Tues: Garner-3, Crawford-1, Condit-1, Selbig-3, Anderson-3, Steil-4
Wed: Murray-5, McKenna-2, Chiazza-2, Glick-1, Lynch-5
Thurs: 6th, Hammond-5, Smith-4, 6th
Fri: Lameris-2, 7th, 7th, 8th, 8th

See you Monday, August 31st for a great first day and YES! We will be going outside for ES on the 1st day of school.

post_text:
WMAES is excited to welcome back our students, both virtually and on campus. We have been preparing to take our learning outside even more during these unprecedented times. Studies have shown that students who learn outdoors develop: a sense of self, independence, confidence, creativity, decision-making and problem-solving skills, empathy towards others, motor skills, self-discipline and initiative. In order for us to make sure students are comfortable and ready to learn this fall, we know they will need some shady areas, and while our 62 acre campus has forests for students to meet and learn, we still need some assistance with keeping cool and shaded.

We are looking for donations of shade tents like this one:
https://www.amazon.com/Keymaya-Commercial-Instant-Shelter-Canopies/dp/B07NR9ZXHQ

If you have one at home that you just don't use anymore or would like to donate a new one to WMAES, please contact Mr. Shawn by email: shawnwessell@choiceschools.com

Have you heard the saying, ‚ÄúTo plant a garden is to believe in tomorrow‚Äù? That‚Äôs what Mr. Shawn and I have been doing this summer, believing in tomorrow while we work in the garden. WMAES received a $3000 Whole Kids Foundation grant this past winter and we are so grateful that we could use this to create a new garden space for our school community! While our plans to create and build our garden with our students didn‚Äôt quite work this spring and summer, Mr. Shawn, myself, and our wonderful maintenance crew have worked hard to get it ready for when students return. We are excited for our two summer camps starting next week where we can share our bounty and work with our students in the garden. A big thank you to Whole Kids Foundation for the grant and for believing in tomorrow with us!
-Ms. Holly-

post_text:
Good Evening WMAES Family!

Yesterday Gov. Whitmer announced the "Return to School Road Map". Our team is currently updating our plans and will be sharing and seeking feedback from all of you throughout the month of July. Thank you for all of your support during this time of uncertainty and know that we want nothing more than to see each of our students' smiling faces in the fall!

We want to answer all of your questions! This is why we have scheduled a virtual town hall on July 30th from 5:30-7:00. Details will be sent closer to the event.

In the meantime, check your email because a more detailed letter was just sent out. Included in the letter is a survey to hear from you. We are doing our very best to openly communicate and do what is best for our students. Our work will continue in the coming weeks as we utilize the Road Map.

Thank you!

Mrs. Barrett, Mr. Bosker, Mr. Vanduinen, Mr. Miller

The food box will include 25# of fresh food including apples, potatoes, oranges, cucumbers, tomato, lettuce, asparagus, cabbage or celery, pepper, zucchini. This food box is open to any person wanting to receive one, first come first serve.

post_text:
Ms. Holly has been getting great responses to some of her online Environmental Science lessons. This poem is from the Sensory Poetry lesson. Thanks for sharing and keep sending them her way!

As me and my mom mowed the lawn,
I see dandelions.
My mom says those are weeds.
My sister picks them and says they smell good.
As I rake picking up shredded grass and I heard the birds sing.
it's the beginning of a beautiful spring.
Mekhi

post_text: Happy Arbor Day! A day that literally translates to ‚Äútree‚Äù day from the Latin origin of the word arbor. It's a holiday that celebrates the planting, upkeep and preservation of trees. At WMAES, we definitely celebrate Arbor day! Over the last 17 years, WMAES has planted on average 300 trees every year around the campus. That's a lot of trees! In honor of Arbor Day, check out the video about some of the different trees at WMAES and don‚Äôt forget to check out Mr. Shawn‚Äôs website for ways you can still celebrate Arbor Day from home.

post_text: WMAES has held an Earth Week celebration for 17 years! During the week students would take part in energy saving activities, plant native trees and plants, take part in sustainability lessons, and have fun learning about how to do their part as citizens to help our planet. This year we are going to have a daily Earth Week Challenge where YOU will be working together as families. As a school community we‚Äôll do our part in our own communities. We‚Äôll post a more detailed challenge each day to Facebook, so check back for your family challenge.

post_text:
WMAES has been participating in the Michigan Green Schools initiative since the 2007-2008 school year. Though our foundation is built upon environmental efforts, we‚Äôve dedicated over 13 years to ensure our students are doing their part for our planet. In order to become a Green School, a school and its students must perform a required number of activities to prove their efforts.

We are proud to say that we reached Evergreen status in the 2019-2020 school year!

Check out our website to learn more about our efforts: https://wma-es.com/wmaes-is-an-evergreen-school/

Happy Read-a-thon Day! WOW, way to keep reading!

When: TODAY!
Time: Anytime that day that suits your families need
What: Spend 45 minutes reading something of your choosing
Why: To celebrate Reading Month and promote at home reading!

Please share your Read-a-thon photos below!

Last week students submitted 155 hours of reading. This week students submitted 353 hours!! :) Keep up the good work.

Here are this week's winners of the Reading Raffle!
Pre-K-1st grade- Huck T.
2nd-3rd grade- Austin K.
4th-5th grade Olivia T.
Winners you can pick out your book when we get back to school!!

Next week will be the last week for the raffle and they will be pulled on Thursday. Please submit your hours before noon, https://forms.gle/TQockTU6yeSHkQx97.

Students can submit a writing piece, a poem, artwork or, a video sharing how compassion has impacted their lives for a chance to win the grand prize!

To learn more and submit your student's work visit: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSc9XpyTFbdwlzkS09dQmQg18IeKh6aFoUy_swnam81gbXt2iQ/viewform

PreK Classroom Winners: drawstring bags, framed certificate

4-8 Student Winners: drawstring bag, certificate, chance to win Family Grand Prize valued at $250 (Family day to a museum or zoo)
9-12 Student Winners: drawstring bag, certificate, chance to win Grand Prize valued at $500 (iPad or laptop)

Change of plans for Feeding Walker Kids food bags:

Unfortunately we will not have Feeding Walker Kids food bags available today due to closures and social distancing practices with our community partners. We are working on an alternative plan. We are in communication with the families on the food bag list that have not had the opportunity to attend our designated food distribution times. If you are on the Friday food list but have not picked up food this week and have not already heard from Ms. Joseph via email, then please email her at alexisjoseph@chocieschools.com. I am sorry for this disruption in service.

I apologize this was not posted on dojo sooner! It was my understanding that I posted it last night. It was a technical error on my part, and I apologize. We will have food for families again on Monday starting at 10:00am.

-Mrs. Barrett

Although school is closed for several weeks, we are providing families with an opportunity to pick up free breakfast and lunch meals for all children age 18 and under. Our intent is to make the meal pick up process as simple as possible. Meals can be picked up by driving into the elementary drop off lane and meals will be brought to you. We will be providing meals during the mandated closure on:

Mondays from 10am-12pm (includes breakfast and lunch for Monday and Tuesday)

Wednesdays from 10am -12pm (Includes breakfast and lunch for Weds, Thurs. and Fri)

Because the situation is complex and evolving, our plans may change. If they do, we‚Äôll let you know.

We are gearing up for the 2020 edition of WMAES Penny Wars! We will be holding our Penny Wars to support the Service Learning Trip. Penny Wars will run from Monday, February 24 through Friday, February 28. Winning class for elementary and secondary will win a pizza party!

Rules for Penny Wars
- students who donate pennies to their class get 1 point per penny toward their final score
- students who bring in any other denomination of money can use that to take points away from other classes by putting it into that class's container

Elementary Classes
- Service Learning students will set up containers in the elementary lobby before school (7:40 - 8:00) and after school (3:10 - 3:30) with containers for each homeroom, students can turn in their money at that time.

Secondary Classes
- 6th hour teachers will each receive a collection jar to keep in their classroom, points will be counted daily and scored for that class.

UPDATE: Training is OVER.

**************

Later today (approx. 1 PM), Walker PD will be conducting a scenario training with the staff at West MI Academy of Environmental Science.

The training will entail what an active threat scenario inside the school may look like & challenge the staff to think critically about the most appropriate & safest response options. No students will be on the school property during this training.

If you live nearby, you may see or hear things that normally would be alarming, given the school setting. We assure you this is only a training & we will provide an update when the session is complete.

Another round of ‚ÄúStop the Bleed‚Äù buckets were delivered last night. This round was so big we needed to use the Prisoner Transport Van to move them all to West MI Academy of Environmental Science.

The buckets will be distributed to each classroom, and are stocked with medical supplies that can be used to treat injuries in the event of a serious accident or active threat incident.

A special thank you to Alpine Avenue Meijer for their support of this project, as well as Intern Ember, who helped fill & deliver them all!

post_text: In honor of Martin Luther King Jr. Day, Mrs. McMann's class read a Scholastic interview with Yolanda King, granddaughter of MLK Jr. The interview is from last year, but this young lady is only two years older than this group of students.
